chan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde von Sponheim was born in 1091. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Theodoricus II. von Are. She died in Ahr, Möllen, Dinslaken, Rhineland, Prussia."},"et":{"1091–":"1091–Surnud","1080–1161":"1080–1161","1122–1146":"1122–1146","1122–1167":"1122–1167","1091–Female":"1091–Surnud","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","1146":"1146","1167":"1167","1122":"1122","um 1122":"umbes 1122","1161":"1161","Altenahr Landkreis Ahrweiler":"Altenahr, Landkreis Ahrweiler, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Altenahr, Ahrweiler, Rheinprovinz, Preußen, Deutschland":"Altenahr, Ahrweiler, Rheinprovinz, Preußen","Ahr, Möllen, Dinslaken, Rhineland, Prussia, German Empire":"Ahr, Möllen, Kreis 